The paper deals with super-resolution theory and its extension to compressive samples and multiple measurement vectors. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a reweighted atomic-norm minimization approach for enhancing sparsity and resolution, which is a common technique in signal processing (cs.SP) and computer vision (cs.CV). The proposed method is also demonstrated via numerical simulations, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper's application to DOA estimation suggests that it may also belong to the Signal Processing (cs.SP) and/or the Sound (cs.SI) sub-categories.
